caption: TABLE I: Experiments on FreeGraspData. Higher metric values (SSR and RSR) indicate better performance. Best performance under each setting is in italic.
description: Table 1 presents the results of experiments conducted on the FreeGraspData dataset.  The table compares the performance of the proposed FreeGrasp method with the ThinkGrasp method [14] across different task difficulty levels and levels of object ambiguity.  Performance is measured using two metrics:  Segmentation Success Rate (SSR) and Reasoning Success Rate (RSR). Higher values for both metrics indicate better performance. The table is organized by task difficulty (Easy, Medium, Hard) and the presence or absence of object ambiguity (with Ambiguity, without Ambiguity).  The best performance for each setting is indicated in italics.

caption: TABLE II: Results of real-world experiments. Higher metric values (SR, PE and SPL) indicate better performance. Best performance under each setting is in italic.
description: Table II presents the results of real-world robotic grasping experiments comparing FreeGrasp and ThinkGrasp across various difficulty levels (Easy, Medium, Hard) with and without object ambiguity.  For each setting, it shows the Success Rate (SR), Path Efficiency (PE), and Success Weighted Path Length (SPL). Higher values for all three metrics indicate better performance. The best performance for each setting is highlighted in italics. The metrics evaluate the success of grasping the target object, efficiency of the actions, and overall performance considering both success and efficiency.
